<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-06-18T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-06-18T18:00:00-05:00" n="221" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d221">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 FEAC/6–1847: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Political Adviser in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Atcheson</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">restricted</hi>
                            </seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-06-18T19:00:00-04:00">June 18,
                                    1947—7 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>223. <gloss target="#t_FEC1">FEC</gloss> 21. <hi rend="italic">Property
                                of War Criminals</hi>. <gloss target="#t_FEC1">FEC</gloss> June 12
                            adopted policy decision of above title. Text follows:</p>
                        <p>[Here follows text of <gloss target="#t_FEC1">FEC</gloss> decision
                            (204/11) printed in <hi rend="italic">Activities of the Far Eastern
                                Commission</hi>, page 101.]</p>
                        <p>This policy paper was delayed for some weeks in Commission because of
                            contention of some members that proceeds of confiscated property and
                            fines should be available for reparations rather than occupation costs.
                            Eventually four veto powers agreed on availability for occupation costs
                            and dissenting members had to accept decision.<note n="91" xml:id="d221fn91">The policy decision was embodied in a directive,
                                serial 81, June 20, sent by the Joint Chiefs of Staff to <gloss target="#t_SCAP1">SCAP</gloss> as <hi rend="smallcaps">War</hi>
                                80637 on June 20, and a copy was sent by the Department of State to
                                the Far Eastern Commission on July 3.</note>
                        </p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Marshall</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>